            <h1 class="post-title">
                How to adopt from PAWSter Care
            </h1>
            <p class="post-meta">
                We have very strict protocols in place for adopting out our shelter cats and dogs. 
                These animals have already been through very difficult times. 
                We need to be 100% certain, without a shadow of a doubt, that they will be placed in 
                loving homes.
            </p>
        </div>
        <hr>
        <div class="post-preview clearfix">
            <div>
            <img src="../img/protocol1.jpg" style="float: left; padding-right: 10px" alt="Meet and Greet with Dogs">
                </div>
            
            <h3 class="post-title">
              1. Meet and Greet
            </h3>
          <p class="post-meta">
                   First, you have to visit the shelter to meet your prospective pet. Seeing their cute photos online is different from meeting them in person. This is where you get to see who will tug at your heartstrings and possibly be a new addition to your home.
              <br>
          </p>

        </div>
        <hr>
        <div class="post-preview clearfix">
            <img src="../img/protocol2.jpg" style="float: right; padding-left: 10px" alt="Application and Interview">
            <h3 class="post-title">
                2. Application and Interview
            </h3>
          <p class="post-meta">
              You need to fill up an application form expressing your intent to adopt your chosen cat or dog. You will also be interviewed at least twice to ensure that you and your chosen pet are a good match and you are able to give them a suitable home.  
          </p>

        </div>
          
          <hr>
        <div class="post-preview clearfix">
            <img src="../img/protocol3.jpg" style="float: left; padding-right: 10px" alt="Shelter Visits">
            <h3 class="post-title">
                3. Shelter Visits
             </h3>
          <p class="post-meta">
            You need to make three (3) separate visits to the shelter to spend time with your prospective pet. This is how you know if your chosen r dog is a good fit. It gives you a chance to bond, or if necessary, pick a different pet that will be a better fit for you and your family.
          </p>
        </div>
          <hr>
        <div class="post-preview clearfix">
            <img src="../img/protocol4.jpg" style="float: right; padding-left: 10px" alt="Home Visit">
            <h3 class="post-title">
                4. Home Visit (Ocular Inspection)
            </h3>
          <p class="post-meta">
              A staff member or volunteer will be assigned to visit your home to meet your other family members (if any). This is also done to ensure that your home will be suitable for your new pet.
          </p> 

        </div>
         
